WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.350 --> 00:00:04.446
NULL:  Every gap, every shortcut, every forgotten door -

2
00:00:04.446 --> 00:00:05.700
I will find it.

3
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:09.525
VEGA:  Not tonight. Welcome to the Aegis Citadel. I'm

4
00:00:09.525 --> 00:00:11.747
Vega, and I'll be your guide.

5
00:00:12.047 --> 00:00:17.042
Every modern organization runs on information. Protect it,

6
00:00:17.042 --> 00:00:20.315
and you thrive. Lose it, and you fall.

7
00:00:21.365 --> 00:00:25.470
VEGA:  Picture an organization's information as a walled city.

8
00:00:25.470 --> 00:00:28.007
At its heart sits the Crown Data -

9
00:00:28.007 --> 00:00:32.112
the records, secrets, and services everyone depends on.

10
00:00:32.412 --> 00:00:34.788
NULL:  I don't want your walls. I want what

11
00:00:34.788 --> 00:00:37.165
they guard - the Crown Data. Lose it

12
00:00:37.165 --> 00:00:39.541
once, and there is no second copy of

13
00:00:39.541 --> 00:00:39.937
trust.

14
00:00:40.237 --> 00:00:43.264
NOVA:  I'm Nova - newly appointed, and honestly new

15
00:00:43.264 --> 00:00:45.534
to all of this. Can we start from

16
00:00:45.534 --> 00:00:46.841
the very beginning?

17
00:00:47.141 --> 00:00:50.948
VEGA:  We will. First, a few words everyone uses

18
00:00:50.948 --> 00:00:53.363
and almost no one defines.

19
00:00:54.413 --> 00:00:56.492
NOVA:  So who writes all of this?

20
00:00:56.792 --> 00:01:00.275
VEGA:  NIST does. Think of them as the standards

21
00:01:00.275 --> 00:01:02.314
lab for digital defense.

22
00:01:03.364 --> 00:01:07.536
VEGA:  The thing we're protecting is an information system.

23
00:01:07.836 --> 00:01:10.215
NOVA:  So... not just a computer?

24
00:01:10.515 --> 00:01:14.312
VEGA:  Far more. The people and processes count too.

25
00:01:15.362 --> 00:01:17.591
NOVA:  And a 'control' is...?

26
00:01:17.891 --> 00:01:23.425
VEGA:  A safeguard. Something deliberate that reduces risk. NIST

27
00:01:23.425 --> 00:01:27.503
SP 800-53 is a giant, organized catalog of

28
00:01:27.503 --> 00:01:27.988
them.

29
00:01:29.038 --> 00:01:31.542
NOVA:  Everyone keeps saying 'risk.'

30
00:01:31.842 --> 00:01:35.182
VEGA:  Risk is likelihood times impact. A threat is

31
00:01:35.182 --> 00:01:38.447
who or what could hurt you; a vulnerability

32
00:01:38.447 --> 00:01:41.408
is the weakness they'd use; risk is the

33
00:01:41.408 --> 00:01:43.761
chance - and the cost - if they

34
00:01:43.761 --> 00:01:43.989
do.

35
00:01:45.039 --> 00:01:49.009
VEGA:  Every control in the catalog serves three goals.

36
00:01:49.009 --> 00:01:50.911
Remember them as C-I-A.

37
00:01:51.211 --> 00:01:55.261
VEGA:  Confidentiality - keep secrets secret. Integrity - keep

38
00:01:55.261 --> 00:01:59.017
data correct and untampered. Availability - keep it

39
00:01:59.017 --> 00:02:00.858
working when you need it.

40
00:02:01.158 --> 00:02:07.062
NOVA:  Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. The reason every guardian exists.

41
00:02:08.112 --> 00:02:10.541
NOVA:  Why does any of this exist?

42
00:02:10.841 --> 00:02:13.748
VEGA:  A law says you must protect systems. A

43
00:02:13.748 --> 00:02:17.037
catalog lists what you can use. A framework

44
00:02:17.037 --> 00:02:19.638
is the process that connects them.

45
00:02:19.938 --> 00:02:23.574
VEGA:  The law is FISMA - the Federal Information

46
00:02:23.574 --> 00:02:28.250
Security Modernization Act. 800-53 is the catalog. The

47
00:02:28.250 --> 00:02:31.972
RMF is the process. Hold those three apart,

48
00:02:31.972 --> 00:02:34.310
and everything else clicks.

49
00:02:35.360 --> 00:02:38.489
NOVA:  Isn't privacy just part of security?

50
00:02:38.789 --> 00:02:42.596
VEGA:  They overlap, but they aim at different things.

51
00:02:42.596 --> 00:02:46.564
In Revision 5, security and privacy finally share

52
00:02:46.564 --> 00:02:47.536
one catalog.

53
00:02:48.586 --> 00:02:52.587
NOVA:  So this 'eight-hundred fifty-three' everyone cites - what

54
00:02:52.587 --> 00:02:53.640
is it, exactly?

55
00:02:53.940 --> 00:02:58.619
VEGA:  A catalog. A giant, well-organized menu of controls

56
00:02:58.619 --> 00:03:00.087
you put to work.

57
00:03:01.137 --> 00:03:04.994
VEGA:  The catalog is organized into twenty families. We'll

58
00:03:04.994 --> 00:03:08.109
walk them as twenty districts of the city.

59
00:03:08.409 --> 00:03:11.401
VEGA:  A district isn't really a place - it's

60
00:03:11.401 --> 00:03:15.810
a family of related safeguards: policies, processes, and

61
00:03:15.810 --> 00:03:17.306
technical controls.

62
00:03:17.606 --> 00:03:20.260
NOVA:  Twenty? That's a lot of ground.

63
00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:23.532
VEGA:  So we'll group them into six layers of

64
00:03:23.532 --> 00:03:27.207
defense. By the end, you'll remember every one.

65
00:03:28.257 --> 00:03:31.884
VEGA:  Every control shares the same anatomy. Learn it

66
00:03:31.884 --> 00:03:34.354
once, and you can read them all.

67
00:03:34.654 --> 00:03:38.627
VEGA:  First the identifier, like AC-6 - the family

68
00:03:38.627 --> 00:03:39.801
and a number.

69
00:03:40.101 --> 00:03:44.035
VEGA:  Then the control itself: the requirement, what you

70
00:03:44.035 --> 00:03:45.373
must actually do.

71
00:03:45.673 --> 00:03:48.177
NOVA:  And the discussion explains it?

72
00:03:48.477 --> 00:03:52.155
VEGA:  It gives context and rationale - helpful, but

73
00:03:52.155 --> 00:03:54.199
not itself a requirement.

74
00:03:54.499 --> 00:04:00.330
VEGA:  Related controls point to neighbors. Enhancements add strength

75
00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:04.751
- AC-6(1) is an enhancement of AC-6. References

76
00:04:04.751 --> 00:04:07.196
point outside the catalog.

77
00:04:07.496 --> 00:04:13.984
ARCHIVIST:  Identifier. Control. Discussion. Related controls. Enhancements. References.

78
00:04:15.034 --> 00:04:19.481
VEGA:  Here's a single control. AC-6, Least Privilege.

79
00:04:19.781 --> 00:04:22.738
NOVA:  Clean. An ID, a title, and what it

80
00:04:22.738 --> 00:04:23.260
means.

81
00:04:24.310 --> 00:04:27.331
VEGA:  When you see a gold card, the Archivist

82
00:04:27.331 --> 00:04:30.585
is reading the catalog's real words - word

83
00:04:30.585 --> 00:04:31.282
for word.

84
00:04:31.582 --> 00:04:35.462
ARCHIVIST:  Employ the principle of least privilege, allowing only

85
00:04:35.462 --> 00:04:39.269
authorized accesses for users (or processes acting on

86
00:04:39.269 --> 00:04:42.790
behalf of users) that are necessary to accomplish

87
00:04:42.790 --> 00:04:44.945
assigned organizational tasks.

88
00:04:45.995 --> 00:04:48.474
NOVA:  People keep saying 'baseline.'

89
00:04:48.774 --> 00:04:52.117
VEGA:  A starting kit of controls - Low, Moderate,

90
00:04:52.117 --> 00:04:54.371
or High, sized to the stakes.

91
00:04:55.421 --> 00:04:58.028
NOVA:  Hold on - where are the Low, Moderate,

92
00:04:58.028 --> 00:04:59.675
and High baselines kept?

93
00:04:59.975 --> 00:05:03.987
VEGA:  Sharp eye. In Revision 5 they moved out,

94
00:05:03.987 --> 00:05:07.097
into a companion book: 800-53B.

95
00:05:07.397 --> 00:05:12.927
800-53 is the catalog of controls. 800-53B holds

96
00:05:12.927 --> 00:05:17.190
the baselines and tailoring guidance.

97
00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:22.111
VEGA:  800-53 doesn't stand alone. It plugs into a

98
00:05:22.111 --> 00:05:26.162
process called the Risk Management Framework.

99
00:05:26.462 --> 00:05:29.567
VEGA:  In plain terms: prepare, decide how much the

100
00:05:29.567 --> 00:05:33.026
system matters, pick controls, put them in place,

101
00:05:33.026 --> 00:05:35.849
check they work, get a leader to approve

102
00:05:35.849 --> 00:05:37.684
it, then watch it forever.

103
00:05:37.984 --> 00:05:41.865
NOVA:  And the catalog is 800-53; the baselines in

104
00:05:41.865 --> 00:05:46.288
800-53B help choose which controls we start with.

105
00:05:46.588 --> 00:05:49.605
VEGA:  We'll walk all seven steps in Act Two.

106
00:05:49.605 --> 00:05:52.463
For now, just know the catalog has a

107
00:05:52.463 --> 00:05:52.860
home.

108
00:05:53.910 --> 00:05:57.053
Three guides ride with you.

109
00:05:57.353 --> 00:06:00.603
NULL:  ...and one rides against you.

110
00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:07.451
VEGA:  Six layers lie ahead. The Outer Walls. The

111
00:06:07.451 --> 00:06:10.307
Watchtowers. The Keepers of the Pact.

112
00:06:10.607 --> 00:06:13.675
VEGA:  The High Council. The Forge. The Vaults and

113
00:06:13.675 --> 00:06:16.529
Lifelines. Then the finale: Siege Night.

114
00:06:17.579 --> 00:06:21.247
One honest note before we ride out.

115
00:06:21.547 --> 00:06:24.721
VEGA:  The story is ours. The control text is

116
00:06:24.721 --> 00:06:27.644
theirs - real, and shown on screen.

117
00:06:28.694 --> 00:06:32.288
VEGA:  Let's make it stick. What's a control? Pause,

118
00:06:32.288 --> 00:06:33.166
and answer.

119
00:06:40.216 --> 00:06:42.388
VEGA:  The answer is B.

120
00:06:43.816 --> 00:06:46.855
NOVA:  Quick check. Where do the baselines live now?

121
00:06:46.855 --> 00:06:48.070
Pause, and answer.

122
00:06:55.120 --> 00:06:57.292
VEGA:  The answer is B.

123
00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:02.017
VEGA:  And how many families guard our city?

124
00:07:09.067 --> 00:07:11.239
VEGA:  The answer is C.

125
00:07:12.667 --> 00:07:15.910
NOVA:  Notebook open. That's the whole map on one

126
00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:16.296
page.

127
00:07:16.596 --> 00:07:20.423
VEGA:  That's your foundation. Next, we ride for the

128
00:07:20.423 --> 00:07:21.443
Outer Walls.

129
00:07:21.743 --> 00:07:24.793
NULL:  I'll be waiting at the gate.
